'''''The Ship''''' is a [[documentary film]] about a [[21st century]] voluntary crew on a six-week journey from the east coast of [[Australia]] to [[Jakarta]], [[Indonesia]] retracing the famous voyage of [[Captain James Cook]] aboard a replica of the ''[[HM Bark Endeavour#Replica vessel|HM Bark Endeavour]]''. The 55 men and women on board - among them the director, producer & cameraman [[Chris Terrill]] - came from several different countries and nationalities. The crew traced Cook's footsteps from one historical landmark to another. All of the volunteers lived and worked as [[18th century]] sailors, but were not required to wear period costumes. "The Ship" had some modern conveniences: a satellite phone for emergencies, and a flush toilet in the lower deck for use while sailing in the [[Great Barrier Reef]]. The show originally aired on the [[BBC]] from [[20 August]] - [[24 September]] [[2002]]. The trip was filmed a year earlier and the episode were the crew were informed of the  [[September 11, 2001 attacks|9/11 attacks]] was shown on [[10 September]] [[2002]].

In October, 2002, [[the History Channel]] in conjunction with the BBC aired its "history adventure reality series". It consisted of 6 episodes with each episode running approximately 60 minutes each.

